29:36.808 --> 29:39.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If Texas wants a smaller one,
they can fund
that.

29:39.611 --> 29:42.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's a serious policy
issue we ought
to be discussing.

29:42.080 --> 29:44.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Chris, you're
absolutely
right that every president comes
out with

29:44.549 --> 29:46.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their optimistic vision for it.

29:46.351 --> 29:50.388 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I think a lot of the
concerns, even from
conservatives, today is that
this 3 percent

29:50.421 --> 29:54.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
number seems incredibly not just
optimistic,
but almost fantastic.

29:54.192 --> 29:59.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, we have got President
Reagan's budget
director saying it would require
206 months

29:59.597 --> 30:02.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of no recession, which has never
seen in U.S.
history.

30:02.967 --> 30:07.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have got the Committee for a
Responsible
Federal Budget, who are not
liberals, by any

30:07.639 --> 30:08.606 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
stretch.

30:08.640 --> 30:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're fairly hawkish of the
budget.

30:10.508 --> 30:13.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have called this extremely
unrealistic
and they have said it's a
combination of -- it

30:13.311 --> 30:15.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
needs a combination of good
policy and good
luck.

30:15.513 --> 30:19.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS EDWARDS: I agree the 3
percent growth
number is pretty aggressive.

30:19.050 --> 30:24.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the president has since the
day he's been
in office been cutting
regulations and he's

30:24.422 --> 30:28.226 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pushing a major tax reform plan
that would
boost growth in the economy.

30:28.259 --> 30:33.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No one knows exactly how much, I
think, additionally
the economy will grow if we make
the economy

30:33.865 --> 30:35.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
more efficient.

30:35.433 --> 30:37.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I'm glad he's pushing in
that direction.

30:37.802 --> 30:41.005 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, you know, it's a good
start.

30:41.039 --> 30:42.874 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are serious reforms here.

30:42.907 --> 30:46.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: So, that's the
trickle-down,
kind of fairy dust story that
conservatives

30:46.945 --> 30:50.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have been trying to tell for
decades now,
and it's never worked.

30:50.481 --> 30:53.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It shouldn't be put forth as,
here's an experiment
we're going to try to see what
happens.

30:53.852 --> 30:58.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, in real time, this
is being
tried in Kansas, where they kind
of bought

30:58.289 --> 31:01.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this trickle-down stuff, cut a
bunch of taxes.

31:01.459 --> 31:06.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're -- not only are they
having lousy
economic outcomes, but their
budget is doing

31:06.698 --> 31:09.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
terribly, and they're having to
cut all kinds
of vital services.

31:09.968 --> 31:13.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's where I take so much
issue with
this budget.

31:13.705 --> 31:16.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Our low-income programs are
effective, efficient.

31:16.507 --> 31:20.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're pushing back on poverty
of our most
vulnerable people.

31:20.178 --> 31:23.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is kind of an ain't broke,
don't fix
it moment for those things.

31:23.114 --> 31:28.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But instead of accepting that,
the budget
takes over $3 trillion away from
these programs

31:28.987 --> 31:33.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and gives it to the wealthy in
regressive
tax cuts, which, frankly, they
don't need.

31:33.191 --> 31:37.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS EDWARDS: I won't say that
-- that's
not right, that they're --
they're proposing

31:37.228 --> 31:40.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a budget-neutral, a
deficit-neutral tax reform
plan.

31:40.698 --> 31:43.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They haven't specified it yet,
but that's
what they're aiming for.

31:43.268 --> 31:46.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's not like they're doing
these cuts,
and it's going to wealthy people
at all.

31:46.771 --> 31:50.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the cuts, they're
saying states should
make up the difference if they
want.

31:50.441 --> 31:54.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And to say that the tax cut idea
is a wild
one is not true.

31:54.812 --> 31:57.382 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The centerpiece is a corporate
tax cut.

31:57.415 --> 31:59.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Obama favored a
corporate tax cut.

31:59.183 --> 32:00.985 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't get around to doing
it.

32:01.019 --> 32:02.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump is putting that front and
center.

32:02.954 --> 32:06.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: So, let me make
a quick proposal
here.

32:06.324 --> 32:10.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chris just said that this is
going to be a
revenue-neutral plan.

32:10.662 --> 32:14.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the way the Bush --
that's the way
the Trump team scores it.

32:14.065 --> 32:16.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we know that's phony
accounting.

32:16.034 --> 32:21.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I say we come back here after
there's an official
score by the CBO, by the JCT,
the groups that

32:21.572 --> 32:25.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
score this without a thumb on
the scale, and
it's going to show seas of red
ink.

32:25.743 --> 32:28.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I would really like to put
your foot to
the fire on that.

32:28.746 --> 32:30.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, when you
look at the
budget, now, let's say you look
up food stamps,

32:31.015 --> 32:32.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the SNAP program, and it says --
there's a
quote there.

32:33.017 --> 32:37.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It says "close eligibility
loopholes, target
benefits to the neediest
households, and require

32:37.522 --> 32:39.357 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
able-bodied adults to work."

32:39.390 --> 32:40.558 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That sounds fair enough.

32:40.591 --> 32:42.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's wrong with that?

32:42.393 --> 32:44.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Well, first of
all, there
already are work requirements
within the food

32:45.029 --> 32:46.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
stamp, or SNAP, program.

32:46.764 --> 32:53.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, almost 90 percent
of people
on SNAP who are able-bodied and
have kids

32:53.771 --> 32:56.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are connected to the job market,
are working
or trying to work.

32:56.975 --> 32:59.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So I think it's a non-solution
to a non-problem.

32:59.510 --> 33:05.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, this is a program that
provides nutritional
support -- $1.40 per person per
meal, that

33:05.516 --> 33:07.285 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is what SNAP affords you.

33:07.318 --> 33:09.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, if you want to look out at
America and
say, boy, that's the problem
that is holding

33:09.854 --> 33:14.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us back, and so we have to cut
that to give
reach people more tax cuts, you
and I have

33:14.092 --> 33:15.660 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a lot to argue about it.

33:15.693 --> 33:18.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Chris, what
about the underlying
demographic shift, right?

33:18.930 --> 33:22.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, millennials are just not
replacing
the number of baby boomers that
are retiring.

33:22.900 --> 33:27.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How are you ever going to have
labor force
at the levels in the '90s that
it requires

33:27.905 --> 33:32.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to increase the productivity and
get us back
to the sort of optimistic vision
this budget

33:32.076 --> 33:33.044 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
lays out?

33:33.077 --> 33:34.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS EDWARDS: I agree that's a
big problem.

33:34.145 --> 33:35.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think the budgets helps
tackle that.

33:35.980 --> 33:40.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for example, with a lot of
the welfare
reforms, the budget director,
Mulvaney wants

33:40.318 --> 33:42.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- he's saying he wants to get
people back
in the work force.

33:42.720 --> 33:46.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a good example here is the
Social Security
disability insurance program.

33:46.858 --> 33:51.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The program, they are going to
be doing a
lot of reforms to try to urge
people back

33:51.829 --> 33:53.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into the work force.

33:53.598 --> 33:58.036 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are probably millions of
people who
have moderate disabilities who
can and want

33:58.069 --> 34:04.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be back in the work force,
but the current
disability program
disincentivizes them.

34:04.075 --> 34:06.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It encourages them to stay out
of the work
force.

34:06.611 --> 34:10.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, if we can make some
of these
reforms, get people back to the
work force,

34:10.782 --> 34:11.749 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that would boost growth.

34:11.783 --> 34:12.750 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

34:12.784 --> 34:13.751 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: I'm sorry.

34:13.785 --> 34:14.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Unfortunately, we're out of
time.

34:14.886 --> 34:20.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chris Edwards, Jared Bernstein,
thank you
both.

34:21.025 --> 34:25.196 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRIS EDWARDS: Thank you.

34:25.229 --> 34:29.434 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Thank you.

34:29.467 --> 34:34.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The president
continued
his lengthy overseas trip today,
ending his

34:34.539 --> 34:38.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stay in Israel and a visit to
the West Bank.

34:38.076 --> 34:41.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was the end of four days in
the Middle
East, after a packed schedule
that included

34:41.512 --> 34:44.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
summits, elaborate dinners, and
high-stakes
meetings.

34:44.248 --> 34:46.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang reports.

34:46.117 --> 34:51.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: President Trump
crossed the imposing
security wall separating Israel
and the West

34:51.289 --> 34:57.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bank to meet with Palestinian
leader Mahmoud
Abbas in Bethlehem, part of Mr.
Trump's quest

34:57.495 --> 35:01.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to jump-start long-dormant
Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks.

35:01.566 --> 35:04.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
I intend to do everything I can
to help them

35:04.769 --> 35:06.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
achieve that goal.

35:06.571 --> 35:12.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Abbas assures me he is
ready to
work toward that goal in good
faith, and Prime

35:12.643 --> 35:17.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Minister Netanyahu has promised
the same.

35:17.315 --> 35:23.488 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Abbas outlined what's
called the
two-state solution, a
Palestinian homeland

35:23.521 --> 35:29.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the territory that Israel
seized 50 years
ago in the Six-Day War.

35:29.093 --> 35:33.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAHMOUD ABBAS, Palestinian
Authority President
(through translator): Our
fundamental problem

35:33.331 --> 35:37.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is with the occupation and
settlements, and
failure of Israel to recognize
the state of

35:37.435 --> 35:39.704 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Palestine, in the same way we
recognize it.

35:39.737 --> 35:43.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It undermines the realization of
a two-state
solution.

35:43.374 --> 35:45.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The problem is not between us
and Judaism.

35:45.543 --> 35:47.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's between us and occupation.

35:47.478 --> 35:52.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Later, speaking in
Jerusalem, Mr.
Trump acknowledged there would
be hurdles.

35:52.683 --> 35:56.220 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Both sides will
face tough decisions.

35:56.254 --> 36:02.927 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But with determination,
compromise and the
belief that peace is possible,
Israelis and

36:02.960 --> 36:05.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Palestinians can make a deal.

36:05.530 --> 36:08.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Missing from Mr.
Trump's comments?

36:08.266 --> 36:13.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
An explicit endorsement of a
two-state solution,
which has been U.S. policy for
more than a

36:13.204 --> 36:15.106 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
quarter-century.

36:15.139 --> 36:18.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Daniel Estrin is Jerusalem
correspondent for
NPR News.

36:18.442 --> 36:23.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL ESTRIN, NPR: He spoke a
lot about peace,
but he was very short on
specifics.

36:23.848 --> 36:26.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that was very emblematic of
his whole
trip here.

36:26.484 --> 36:31.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't want to wade into any
thorny issues.

36:31.389 --> 36:33.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't talk about a two-state
solution.

36:33.991 --> 36:37.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He didn't talk about Israeli
assessments in
the West Bank, where
Palestinians want to

36:37.929 --> 36:40.031 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
build a Palestinian state.

36:40.064 --> 36:42.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't talk about the U.S.
Embassy.

36:42.233 --> 36:45.002 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This trip was much more about
smiles.

36:45.036 --> 36:47.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It was much more about
relationship-building.

36:47.171 --> 36:52.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Do you see much
reason for optimism
that President Trump is going to
get these

36:52.510 --> 36:54.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
talks, this peace process going
again?

36:54.679 --> 36:56.814 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DANIEL ESTRIN: Clinton tried.

36:56.847 --> 36:57.815 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Bush tried.

36:57.848 --> 36:59.016 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Obama tried.

36:59.050 --> 37:00.851 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They all failed at bringing
peace.

37:00.885 --> 37:05.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so many people I spoke to
here, Israelis
and Palestinians, said, why
should Trump be

37:05.556 --> 37:07.391 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
any different?

37:07.425 --> 37:12.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I even met a Palestinian woman
yesterday who
said she read Trump's book "How
to Get Rich."

37:12.363 --> 37:18.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She admired Trump's business
success, but
she said, that doesn't translate
into making

37:18.102 --> 37:20.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
someone a peacemaker.

37:20.037 --> 37:25.443 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, while there is that
cynicism, there are
also people on both sides who
think that actually

37:25.476 --> 37:29.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump perhaps might be the one
to seal the
deal.

37:29.347 --> 37:33.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: On the last day of
his Israel stop,
Mr. Trump visited Yad Vashem,
the nation's

37:33.884 --> 37:35.653 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
