Despite the gulf separating them
in terms
of personality and policies,
Pope Francis

38:49.994 --> 38:51.796 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
insists he has an open mind.

38:51.829 --> 38:56.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
POPE FRANCIS, Leader of Catholic
Church (through
translator): I never make a
judgment about

38:56.934 --> 38:58.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a person without listening to
them.

38:58.936 --> 39:00.771 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't think I should do that.

39:00.805 --> 39:05.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Massimo Franco,
a Vatican
expert with Italy's most
respected newspaper,

39:05.943 --> 39:09.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says that President Trump
instigated the meeting
and has the most to gain.

39:09.413 --> 39:12.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASSIMO FRANCO, Corriere della
Sera: This
meeting is more important for
Trump than for

39:12.516 --> 39:20.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the pope, because Trump
presently is very
weak internally, so he needs a
more international

39:20.291 --> 39:22.093 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
reach.

39:22.126 --> 39:24.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: International
relations specialist
Professor Irene Caratelli goes
further.

39:24.729 --> 39:29.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IRENE CARATELLI, International
Relations Specialist:
It's about legitimacy, so he's
looking for

39:29.567 --> 39:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a sort of blessing from the
pope.

39:31.869 --> 39:36.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He wants to be recognized by all
the different
figures of the world.

39:36.540 --> 39:40.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But Father John
Wauck, an
American speechwriter before he
was ordained,

39:40.845 --> 39:41.846 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
says there's a mutual benefit.

39:41.879 --> 39:43.581 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REV.

39:43.614 --> 39:45.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN WAUCK, Catholic Church: The
Catholic
Church is always interested in
its relations

39:45.416 --> 39:49.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with the United States, given
the importance
of the U.S. on the international
political

39:49.720 --> 39:55.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scene, largely because there's
an enormous
number of issues in which the
Catholic Church

39:55.059 --> 39:56.861 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
can cooperate.

39:56.894 --> 40:00.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But one
potential stumbling
block is the history of sharp
criticism over

40:00.831 --> 40:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a major Trump election pledge.

40:02.666 --> 40:08.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: We must restore
integrity and
the rule of law at our borders.

40:08.339 --> 40:10.174 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

40:10.207 --> 40:16.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: For that reason,
we will soon
begin the construction of a
great, great wall

40:16.580 --> 40:18.816 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
along our southern border.

40:18.849 --> 40:20.684 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

40:20.718 --> 40:26.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
POPE FRANCIS (through
translator): A person
who thinks only about building
walls, wherever

40:26.190 --> 40:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they may be, and not building
bridges is not
Christian.

40:29.927 --> 40:35.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: For a religious
leader to question
a person's faith is disgraceful.

40:35.466 --> 40:40.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: This biography
of Pope Francis
by veteran Vatican correspondent
David Willey

40:40.371 --> 40:45.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
portrays the pontiff as a frugal
man who abstains
from the luxurious trappings of
office and

40:45.910 --> 40:49.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tries to maintain contact with
the poor, especially
refugees.

40:49.580 --> 40:54.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, after visiting the
Greek island
of Lesbos, he brought three
Syrian families

40:54.618 --> 40:56.487 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
back to Rome.

40:56.520 --> 40:59.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WILLEY, Author, "The
Promise of Francis":
The pope is very concerned with
the situation

40:59.156 --> 41:01.258 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of refugees all over the world.

41:01.292 --> 41:06.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think the pope will
hesitate to say
exactly what he thinks about
controversial

41:06.797 --> 41:15.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
subjects, particularly about,
for example,
President Trump's plan to deport
many hundreds

41:15.940 --> 41:19.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of thousands, if not millions of
illegal migrants
in the United States.

41:19.710 --> 41:23.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Today, at the
Vatican, the
pope condemned the barbarity of
the terrorist

41:23.714 --> 41:25.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bomb in Manchester.

41:25.349 --> 41:27.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The attack may affect the issues
under discussion.

41:27.952 --> 41:33.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MASSIMO FRANCO: Trump and the
pope are against
terrorism, of course, but I
think that the

41:33.557 --> 41:40.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
approach of the pope is more on
the causes,
on the source of Islamic
terrorism.

41:41.031 --> 41:47.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The pope tends to say that it is
not Islamic
terrorism, but it is terrorists
motivated

41:48.005 --> 41:50.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
falsely with religious reasons.

41:50.741 --> 41:52.610 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REV.

41:52.643 --> 41:55.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN WAUCK: Donald Trump's
statements recently
in Saudi Arabia, I think, made
him sound quite

41:55.546 --> 42:01.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a bit more like the pope, in
other words,
emphasizing that this is not a
battle between

42:01.285 --> 42:05.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one religion and another, and
stressing the
need for peace and all.

42:05.122 --> 42:07.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think there's going to be
some common
ground there.

42:07.191 --> 42:10.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Certainly, there will be common
ground on
things like human trafficking,
maybe less

42:10.661 --> 42:14.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so on the questions of climate
change, if
that comes up.

42:14.298 --> 42:19.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: According to
veteran Vatican
watchers, one of the key factors
in determining

42:19.036 --> 42:23.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether or not this meeting has
been a success
will be its duration.

42:23.574 --> 42:28.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the meeting ends after about
15 minutes
or so, that will be a bad sign,
because, they

42:28.312 --> 42:32.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say, it will suggest that Pope
Francis has
cut the meeting short.

42:32.750 --> 42:36.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the experts believe there
are strong reasons
to lay foundations for the
future.

42:36.220 --> 42:41.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
IRENE CARATELLI: I think that
Pope Francis
is going to meet President
Trump, knowing

42:41.825 --> 42:45.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he has the possibility to
influence someone
who can change history.

42:45.362 --> 42:51.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WILLEY: I think that both
of them are
canny people who realize the
advantages of

42:51.502 --> 42:56.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a face-to-face meeting and will
-- both of
them will be absolutely
fascinated to see

42:56.974 --> 42:58.943 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
each other in the flesh for the
first time.

42:58.976 --> 43:02.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Most experts
doubt that President
Trump will change his views
substantially

43:02.980 --> 43:07.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Rome, but they think at least
the two men
will have a new understanding of
each other.

43:07.318 --> 43:13.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Rome.

43:13.290 --> 43:23.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: As we
discussed before,
the Trump administration's
budget proposes

43:23.400 --> 43:26.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
major cuts to a number of
federal agencies
and initiatives.

43:26.770 --> 43:31.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We wanted to take a deeper look
at the proposed
cuts with regards to education
and a push

43:31.842 --> 43:35.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for expanding school choice with
some of those
dollars.

43:35.412 --> 43:39.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
William Brangham has that story,
which is
part of our weekly series Making
the Grade.

43:39.049 --> 43:44.088 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The
administration's budget
proposes roughly $9 billion in
cuts to various

43:44.121 --> 43:46.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
federal education programs.

43:46.090 --> 43:48.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's about a 13 percent
reduction.

43:48.359 --> 43:52.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A billion from those cuts would
be rerouted
to advance school choice, where
parents can

43:52.730 --> 43:56.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take public school funds and
spend it on any
school they choose.

43:56.600 --> 43:59.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Secretary of Education of Betsy
DeVos praised
that idea in a speech yesterday.

43:59.870 --> 44:03.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BETSY DEVOS, U.S. Education
Secretary: We
must offer the widest number of
quality options

44:03.941 --> 44:07.878 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to every family and every child.

44:07.911 --> 44:13.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Empowering parents with choices
is how to
give students second, third or
fourth chances

44:13.450 --> 44:16.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
before it's too late.

44:16.153 --> 44:20.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Even the most expensive,
state-of-the-art,
high-performing school will not
be the perfect

44:20.391 --> 44:23.494 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
fit for every single child.

44:23.527 --> 44:28.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parents know or they can figure
out what learning
environment is best for their
child.

44:28.766 --> 44:32.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: For more on
what this all
means for students nationwide,
I'm joined

44:32.603 --> 44:34.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
now by Anya Kamenetz.

44:34.538 --> 44:39.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's an education reporter for
NPR and the
author of several books on the
future of education.

44:39.710 --> 44:42.279 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Anya, welcome to the "NewsHour."

44:42.312 --> 44:46.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's talk about -- before we
get to the broader
issue of the budget, let's talk
about school

44:46.050 --> 44:47.951 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
choice.

44:47.985 --> 44:51.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has obviously been a huge
issue for Secretary
DeVos, one that she has
championed for many,

44:51.388 --> 44:53.190 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
many years.

44:53.223 --> 44:57.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Remind us what school choice
means and what
this budget does with regard to
school choice.

44:57.528 --> 45:01.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANYA KAMENETZ, NPR: So, school
choice is a
catch-all term.

45:01.165 --> 45:07.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It can mean sending students to
charter schools,
which are alternative public
schools, or using

45:07.604 --> 45:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vouchers to send them to private
schools,
or even using vouchers for
homeschooling or

45:12.476 --> 45:14.244 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
online and virtual schools.

45:14.278 --> 45:18.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all of those are embraced by
Secretary
DeVos.

45:18.682 --> 45:23.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The budget proposal that we're
seeing promotes
choice in a lot of different
ways.

45:23.687 --> 45:28.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there's more money in it for
states to
expand charter programs.

45:28.192 --> 45:34.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is money for states that
want to give
poor students open enrollment
and the chances

45:34.832 --> 45:39.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to leave their low-performing
schools for
other schools within the
district, as well

45:39.269 --> 45:43.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as money for voucher programs,
which, again,
promote private schools.

45:43.373 --> 45:47.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And school
choice obviously
is a very controversial topic.

45:47.444 --> 45:52.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Critics of it think of it as a
way of draining
money away from public schools
and putting

45:52.049 --> 45:56.120 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
them into private or religious
schools.

45:56.153 --> 45:59.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What does the data tell us on
how good these
schools are?

46:00.023 --> 46:01.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does school choice do for
kids?

46:02.025 --> 46:05.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANYA KAMENETZ: Well, as you
mentioned, this
is a really contentious issue,
and there is

46:05.929 --> 46:07.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kind of a moving target.

46:07.531 --> 46:10.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of different
arguments for,
against and around school
choice.

46:10.901 --> 46:15.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, recently, in looking at the
research,
I think one thing that we can
say is that

46:15.506 --> 46:18.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there do seem to be positive
competition effects.

46:18.108 --> 46:23.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In other words, public schools
perk up when
there's a new sheriff in town.

46:23.480 --> 46:28.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, when you talk
about students,
especially poor students,
leaving their schools

46:28.185 --> 46:32.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and going out to schools of
choice, charter
schools, private schools, there
is controversy

46:32.422 --> 46:33.423 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

46:33.457 --> 46:35.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In some cases, they may do a
little bit better.

46:35.826 --> 46:37.928 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In other cases, in fact, they do
worse.

46:37.961 --> 46:43.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And some of the most recent
studies on voucher
programs in particular in
Louisiana, in Ohio

46:43.600 --> 46:49.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and in Washington, D.C., have
shown declines
in performance when students
leave for private

46:49.740 --> 46:51.575 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
schools.

46:51.608 --> 46:54.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's really notable,
because, when you
look at education research, a
lot of times,

46:54.344 --> 46:58.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's no effect, sometimes,
there's positive
effects, but to find a negative
effect is

46:58.081 --> 46:59.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a little bit unusual.

46:59.883 --> 47:02.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
let's go back
to this larger issue of the
budget itself,

47:02.152 --> 47:03.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
$9 billion in cuts.

47:03.420 --> 47:06.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of these will fall on
higher education
in particular.

47:06.323 --> 47:07.991 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can you tell us about those
cuts?

47:08.025 --> 47:09.760 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANYA KAMENETZ: Absolutely.

47:09.793 --> 47:14.898 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the biggest item here is an
end to subsidized
student loans.

47:14.932 --> 47:19.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Right now, there's two student
loan programs
for subsidized loans.

47:19.136 --> 47:24.241 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If you qualify, for
undergraduates, the government
picks up your interest while
you're in school.

47:24.274 --> 47:27.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that would be going away
under this plan.

47:27.377 --> 47:32.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The second really significant
cut is in the
loan repayment program called
public service

47:32.149 --> 47:34.051 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
loan forgiveness.

47:34.084 --> 47:39.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is for teachers,
doctors, firefighters,
police officers, people engaged
in nonprofits

47:39.556 --> 47:41.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and government work.

47:41.091 --> 47:45.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were supposed to have their
loans forgiven
after 10 years of service.

47:45.462 --> 47:47.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this program's only 10 years
old.

47:47.865 --> 47:52.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if you're following along,
the repayment
was supposed to start this
October.

47:52.569 --> 47:55.772 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And all -- upwards of
half-a-million people
are enrolled in this program.

47:55.806 --> 47:59.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it goes away, it would be a
big panic for
a lot of people.

47:59.209 --> 48:02.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On top of that, there's cuts to
a number of
different programs.

48:02.646 --> 48:04.481 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's flat funding for Pell.

48:04.514 --> 48:09.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a small program that
might be going
away would be child care for
college students.

48:09.086 --> 48:13.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's significant for
working students
who we see at many of our
community colleges,

48:13.457 --> 48:15.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for example.

48:15.259 --> 48:17.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Obviously,
this is just
the president's proposal, and
Congress still

48:17.594 --> 48:19.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has to weigh in on this.

48:19.396 --> 48:24.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How likely do you think it is
that this budget
will remain intact going through
Congress?

48:24.134 --> 48:30.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANYA KAMENETZ: I mean, I'm sure
you have got
a lot of people giving this a
negative handicap.

48:30.474 --> 48:34.711 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the K-12 side, there's broad
bipartisan
support for a lot of these
proposals that

48:34.745 --> 48:36.546 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are under the gun here in.

48:36.580 --> 48:41.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In higher ed, some of these cuts
could be
made with budget reconciliation
without any

48:41.551 --> 48:46.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
